things went smoothly, but...

286
00:16:15,500 --> 00:16:17,500
What's wrong, Prime Minister?

287
00:16:20,200 --> 00:16:21,600
Kodaira.

288
00:16:22,100 --> 00:16:24,800
During the war,
you were on a suicide squad.

289
00:16:25,100 --> 00:16:26,700
Before your mission,

290
00:16:26,800 --> 00:16:28,300
the war ended.

291
00:16:29,300 --> 00:16:32,000
Now you go in and out of prison.

292
00:16:33,300 --> 00:16:35,800
Up to now, 7 times.

293
00:16:36,000 --> 00:16:37,200
No.

294
00:16:37,400 --> 00:16:38,600
8.

295
00:16:38,700 --> 00:16:39,900
Sorry.

296
00:16:40,200 --> 00:16:41,800
After 8 times,

297
00:16:41,900 --> 00:16:43,600
you're now a good citizen.

298
00:16:43,900 --> 00:16:47,200
How about the Health Minister?

299
00:16:47,300 --> 00:16:49,000
You like that?

300
00:16:49,800 --> 00:16:51,000
No.

301
00:16:51,600 --> 00:16:55,300
I want to be Chief of Police.

302
00:16:55,800 --> 00:16:57,300
That's sarcastic.

303
00:16:57,500 --> 00:16:59,900
Cynical and funny!

304
00:17:00,500 --> 00:17:02,600
Thinking in the same direction,

305
00:17:03,000 --> 00:17:06,800
Army Minister is more interesting!

306
00:17:06,900 --> 00:17:09,600
Prime Minister!
That doesn't work!

307
00:17:10,200 --> 00:17:11,900
Our country is...

308
00:17:12,100 --> 00:17:15,700
without war and anti-war.

309
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:19,400
And we hoist the flags
of real peace!

310
00:17:19,500 --> 00:17:22,000
To hoist those flags,

311
00:17:22,300 --> 00:17:26,000
an Army Minister is necessary,
Foreign Minister.

312
00:17:26,100 --> 00:17:30,600
When I hear the words
of "Army Minister",

313
00:17:31,300 --> 00:17:34,800
Whenever I remember
some professors saying,

314
00:17:35,300 --> 00:17:40,700
"A country without military
power is not a country!"

315
00:17:40,800 --> 00:17:43,000
I feel a chill.

316
00:17:43,500 --> 00:17:46,100
Goose pimples! Look!

317
00:17:46,200 --> 00:17:47,600
Where?

318
00:17:47,800 --> 00:17:50,000
What I want...

319
00:17:50,300 --> 00:17:52,000
isn't military power,

320
00:17:52,900 --> 00:17:55,300
but deterrence power.

321
00:17:56,400 --> 00:17:58,000
Because our country...

322
00:17:58,700 --> 00:18:01,200
will be surrounded by Japan and others.

323
00:18:01,800 --> 00:18:03,400
When that time comes,

324
00:18:03,500 --> 00:18:06,100
we have no allies.

325
00:18:06,200 --> 00:18:07,600
What to do?

326
00:18:08,600 --> 00:18:10,700
So deterrence power...

327
00:18:10,800 --> 00:18:14,200
means defending
against foreign invasion?

328
00:18:15,600 --> 00:18:16,800
Oh.

329
00:18:17,200 --> 00:18:19,000
Deterrence power.

330
00:18:25,500 --> 00:18:28,000
What country is it?

331
00:18:30,600 --> 00:18:32,500
Yamatai.

332
00:18:35,900 --> 00:18:38,000
Where is it?

333
00:18:39,500 --> 00:18:41,200
Is it... here?

334
00:18:41,600 --> 00:18:43,000
Also here.

335
00:18:43,500 --> 00:18:45,800
We were drifters.

336
00:18:46,800 --> 00:18:48,700
Drifting here and there.

337
00:18:49,300 --> 00:18:51,700
To where there is work.

338
00:18:52,000 --> 00:18:54,900
We've been to many places.

339
00:18:55,500 --> 00:18:58,800
Underpasses of
Sanya, Ueno, Shinjuku.

340
00:19:00,200 --> 00:19:02,000
So you're vagabonds.

341
00:19:02,200 --> 00:19:03,400
Hey!

342
00:19:05,600 --> 00:19:08,600
Now we have our territory.

343
00:19:09,700 --> 00:19:12,600
And our border.

344
00:19:13,100 --> 00:19:14,600
Why are you here?

345
00:19:14,700 --> 00:19:16,100
Today,

346
00:19:16,300 --> 00:19:18,800
we paid a state visit...

347
00:19:18,900 --> 00:19:22,700
to the Diet of Japan.

348
00:19:27,800 --> 00:19:29,400
Before we left,

349
00:19:29,600 --> 00:19:32,200
we ate at the senators' canteen.

350
00:19:33,000 --> 00:19:35,100
It was a state visit,
so we thought...

351
00:19:35,200 --> 00:19:37,200
Japan would pay for our meals.

352
00:19:37,400 --> 00:19:40,600
But they didn't.
What misers!

353
00:19:40,800 --> 00:19:44,200
Finance Minister
was at the bicycle races.

354
00:19:44,300 --> 00:19:46,400
So we got into trouble.

355
00:19:46,800 --> 00:19:48,100
What?

356
00:19:48,300 --> 00:19:50,000
You jumped your bills.

357
00:19:50,700 --> 00:19:51,900
Good.

358
00:19:52,000 --> 00:19:54,000
No... violence.

359
00:19:54,100 --> 00:19:56,400
You tried to rape someone!

360
00:20:00,700 --> 00:20:02,000
Finance Minister!

361
00:20:02,500 --> 00:20:03,800
Finance?

362
00:20:05,300 --> 00:20:07,000
Sorry!

363
00:20:07,400 --> 00:20:10,400
I won three races,

364
00:20:10,500 --> 00:20:12,800
so I stayed until the last race.

365
00:20:12,900 --> 00:20:15,700
To continue my luck
I went to play pachinko.

366
00:20:15,800 --> 00:20:18,100
I won all these!

367
00:20:18,800 --> 00:20:22,300
Did you pay our bills?
It's 10,625 yen.

368
00:20:22,700 --> 00:20:24,900
I did. So,

369
00:20:25,100 --> 00:20:27,800
you can leave now.

370
00:20:28,100 --> 00:20:31,200
It's very late, may I...

371
00:20:31,400 --> 00:20:33,000
stay the night here?

372
00:20:33,100 --> 00:20:35,200
Please open up and let me in.

373
00:20:35,500 --> 00:20:37,900
Let me have breakfast too.

374
00:20:38,000 --> 00:20:40,100
It's free, right?

375
00:20:40,300 --> 00:20:42,100
Excuse me.

376
00:20:42,300 --> 00:20:43,500
Oh.

377
00:20:43,600 --> 00:20:46,500
Hey kid, what did you do?

378
00:20:46,890 --> 00:20:49,600
Doctor Game?

379
00:20:54,800 --> 00:20:57,900
I'm so sorry for my brother.

380
00:21:03,900 --> 00:21:06,300
Their treatments,

381
00:21:07,700 --> 00:21:10,300
may I pay for that?

382
00:21:12,900 --> 00:21:14,200
How much?

383
00:21:15,300 --> 00:21:17,000
I've prepared... this.

384
00:21:17,100 --> 00:21:18,800
- 10 million!
- Stupid!

385
00:21:19,100 --> 00:21:21,600
1 million.

386
00:21:24,500 --> 00:21:25,800
I see.

387
00:21:28,200 --> 00:21:30,500
May we two talk about it?

388
00:21:32,320 --> 00:21:33,700
Yes.

389
00:21:37,000 --> 00:21:38,200
Come.

390
00:21:53,000 --> 00:21:54,800
Are you blind?

391
00:21:55,000 --> 00:21:56,600
- What?
- Tamiko!

392
00:21:57,900 --> 00:21:59,100
What?

393
00:21:59,200 --> 00:22:00,500
Toilet!

394
00:22:01,700 --> 00:22:04,000
I didn't expect that!

395
00:22:04,100 --> 00:22:06,400
I thought it's just 100,000!

396
00:22:06,500 --> 00:22:08,800
Me too, Yumi!

397
00:22:08,900 --> 00:22:11,200
- We can go to Hawaii!
- Am I dreaming?

398
00:22:19,800 --> 00:22:21,700
<i>It's vacant!</i>

399
00:22:25,800 --> 00:22:27,000
What?

400
00:22:27,200 --> 00:22:28,600
What, punk?

401
00:22:41,400 --> 00:22:44,600
So the Yamatai statesmen
are leaving us?

402
00:22:44,700 --> 00:22:48,000
Do you think this is funny?
This is not funny!

403
00:22:48,300 --> 00:22:49,700
Any toothpicks?

404
00:22:49,800 --> 00:22:51,200
You're really crazy.

405
00:22:51,300 --> 00:22:53,900
Go see a doctor.
You have your insurance cards?

406
00:22:54,000 --> 00:22:55,900
We don't.

407
00:22:56,000 --> 00:22:58,500
- We tore them up.
- Tore them up?

408
00:22:58,600 --> 00:23:02,400
"Yen" is our currency,
so we didn't tear them up.

409
00:23:02,500 --> 00:23:04,300
All things issued by Japan,

410
00:23:04,400 --> 00:23:06,400
we tore them up yesterday.

411
00:23:08,500 --> 00:23:11,000
Tax reminders, bus passes,

412
00:23:11,100 --> 00:23:12,600
pension cards,

413
00:23:12,700 --> 00:23:15,100
- policewomen's...
- Policewomen?

414
00:23:15,300 --> 00:23:16,800
Recruitment posters.

415
00:23:16,900 --> 00:23:18,400
Stop kidding!

416
00:23:19,200 --> 00:23:21,300
If they sent us draft notices,

417
00:23:21,900 --> 00:23:23,200
those too.

418
00:23:24,700 --> 00:23:27,300
Will they draft you old men?

419
00:23:28,100 --> 00:23:30,500
You'll never know,
Japan these days...

420
00:23:44,700 --> 00:23:46,000
Jiro.

421
00:23:47,400 --> 00:23:50,300
What is this music?

422
00:23:50,900 --> 00:23:52,300
The Charleston.

423
00:23:53,300 --> 00:23:54,700
What is it?

424
00:23:55,200 --> 00:23:56,600
Lately,

425
00:23:58,600 --> 00:24:00,600
I don't know why,

426
00:24:01,900 --> 00:24:03,600
this is funny to me.

427
