1380
01:18:14,300 --> 01:18:16,500
5 million.
The rest, tomorrow.

1381
01:18:17,200 --> 01:18:18,500
Jiro?

1382
01:18:19,000 --> 01:18:20,500
Also tomorrow.

1383
01:18:21,300 --> 01:18:23,000
I'll kill him.

1384
01:18:23,600 --> 01:18:25,500
- A long trip?
- Yes.

1385
01:18:26,400 --> 01:18:28,300
1 year in Sri Lanka.

1386
01:18:29,200 --> 01:18:30,500
See you.

1387
01:18:32,500 --> 01:18:34,000
<i>August 14.</i>

1388
01:18:35,300 --> 01:18:37,000
<i>A lavish breakfast.</i>

1389
01:18:38,500 --> 01:18:41,200
<i>Actually, Finance Minister's
funds have run out.</i>

1390
01:18:42,000 --> 01:18:45,600
<i>One dried plum each
to go with the rice.</i>

1391
01:18:50,400 --> 01:18:52,500
Telephone, gas, electricity.

1392
01:18:53,100 --> 01:18:55,000
Water is next.

1393
01:18:56,100 --> 01:18:59,600
But you've all lived
through the war.

1394
01:19:00,200 --> 01:19:02,200
You're all survivors.

1395
01:19:02,400 --> 01:19:05,500
Now's the time
to repeat the experience.

1396
01:19:05,900 --> 01:19:08,600
You can do it again.

1397
01:19:08,700 --> 01:19:11,500
To us, this is just camping.

1398
01:19:11,700 --> 01:19:13,100
- Right?
- Yes.

1399
01:19:13,800 --> 01:19:15,100
The thing...

1400
01:19:15,600 --> 01:19:17,800
is what will come next, for sure.

1401
01:19:18,000 --> 01:19:19,400
Air raids.

1402
01:19:20,100 --> 01:19:21,800
Well I...

1403
01:19:22,000 --> 01:19:25,200
had a freaky experience
in the first raid.

1404
01:19:26,100 --> 01:19:28,400
The Doolittle Raid
was the first on Japan.

1405
01:19:28,800 --> 01:19:31,200
The Hornet bombers came...

1406
01:19:31,500 --> 01:19:33,200
and dropped the bombs.

1407
01:19:33,400 --> 01:19:36,500
B-25 bombers flew
all the way from China.

1408
01:19:37,300 --> 01:19:38,800
At that time,

1409
01:19:38,900 --> 01:19:43,000
I was eating noodles
at an eatery in Sendagaya.

1410
01:19:43,500 --> 01:19:44,900
And then,

1411
01:19:45,100 --> 01:19:47,900
the bicycle shop the next door
from the next...

1412
01:19:50,000 --> 01:19:52,000
You're lucky.

1413
01:19:52,500 --> 01:19:56,000
I think the life line
on my palm saved me.

1414
01:19:57,000 --> 01:19:58,900
Look. Look.

1415
01:19:59,700 --> 01:20:01,300
Very long, to here.

1416
01:20:01,900 --> 01:20:03,200
Let me...

1417
01:20:03,700 --> 01:20:06,400
Lots of memories.

1418
01:20:07,200 --> 01:20:09,900
What I meant by air raids...

1419
01:20:10,600 --> 01:20:13,600
is that an army, no.

1420
01:20:14,200 --> 01:20:16,400
Thugs or gangsters...

1421
01:20:16,700 --> 01:20:19,800
will attack us for sure.

1422
01:20:20,500 --> 01:20:23,300
How would our army
deal with that?

1423
01:20:25,800 --> 01:20:27,500
If we have to fight,

1424
01:20:28,900 --> 01:20:30,300
fight bravely.

1425
01:20:30,600 --> 01:20:31,900
Bravely?

1426
01:20:32,500 --> 01:20:34,400
Yes! We shouldn't...

1427
01:20:34,500 --> 01:20:36,900
forget the meaning of life!

1428
01:20:38,100 --> 01:20:39,700
At that time,

1429
01:20:40,200 --> 01:20:43,600
all we thought about,

1430
01:20:43,600 --> 01:20:47,000
was how to die in dignity
if it's inevitable.

1431
01:20:47,900 --> 01:20:49,200
Oh yes!

1432
01:20:50,000 --> 01:20:51,600
Humans die!

1433
01:20:52,100 --> 01:20:53,300
Yes.

1434
01:20:53,700 --> 01:20:57,300
You never thought about it,
Interior Minister?

1435
01:20:57,700 --> 01:20:59,300
Prime Minister...

1436
01:20:59,500 --> 01:21:01,600
not just "at that time",

1437
01:21:02,000 --> 01:21:04,200
lately,

1438
01:21:04,600 --> 01:21:06,900
I feel that way.
I don't know why.

1439
01:21:07,500 --> 01:21:08,900
You too?

1440
01:21:10,200 --> 01:21:14,600
It's the fate of our
Charleston generation.

1441
01:21:15,800 --> 01:21:18,800
The Charleston is popular
these days.

1442
01:21:19,100 --> 01:21:20,800
Yes, Labour Minister.

1443
01:21:21,500 --> 01:21:23,600
We were all born and raised...

1444
01:21:23,700 --> 01:21:25,900
when the Charleston was popular.

1445
01:21:28,400 --> 01:21:30,200
But, Labour Minister,

1446
01:21:31,100 --> 01:21:33,300
what's a little bit disturbing...

1447
01:21:33,700 --> 01:21:36,600
is that its lively rhythm,

1448
01:21:37,000 --> 01:21:39,500
without people noticing,

1449
01:21:39,700 --> 01:21:42,900
was replaced by militarism.

1450
01:21:43,200 --> 01:21:44,900
I don't think so.

1451
01:21:45,300 --> 01:21:47,800
You all have some
sort of war allergy.

1452
01:21:48,000 --> 01:21:49,300
Really?

1453
01:21:51,600 --> 01:21:53,000
Personally,

1454
01:21:53,200 --> 01:21:55,300
before my body aches
here and there,

1455
01:21:56,000 --> 01:21:58,500
when I hear
<i>When The Saints Go Marching In</i>,

1456
01:21:58,900 --> 01:22:02,200
I feel I could just die happily.

1457
01:22:02,800 --> 01:22:05,100
That's great. I'll go there too.

1458
01:22:05,200 --> 01:22:06,700
Really?

1459
01:22:07,000 --> 01:22:09,000
If you say,
"do it for your country",

1460
01:22:09,100 --> 01:22:11,800
I can understand the
nature of this country.

1461
01:22:12,300 --> 01:22:13,900
But not that one.

1462
01:22:14,000 --> 01:22:15,900
You don't understand?

1463
01:22:16,300 --> 01:22:17,600
Listen.

1464
01:22:17,900 --> 01:22:21,000
"For your country" but why?
I didn't understand then.

1465
01:22:21,300 --> 01:22:23,600
And I don't understand now either.

1466
01:22:24,600 --> 01:22:26,300
"There are too many citizens,"

1467
01:22:26,600 --> 01:22:29,700
"we can't take care of everyone."

1468
01:22:30,200 --> 01:22:32,000
"Our territory..."

1469
01:22:32,600 --> 01:22:34,300
"that is..."

1470
01:22:34,400 --> 01:22:37,000
"becoming the Fujiyama..."

1471
01:22:37,300 --> 01:22:39,400
Politics is...

1472
01:22:39,500 --> 01:22:41,700
just a political party,

1473
01:22:42,000 --> 01:22:44,800
and the black veil it creates.

1474
01:22:45,600 --> 01:22:47,500
I don't want to die...

1475
01:22:48,000 --> 01:22:49,500
for these things.

1476
01:22:49,800 --> 01:22:51,200
I hate it!

1477
01:22:53,200 --> 01:22:56,000
I hate to hear you
talk about dying!

1478
01:22:58,200 --> 01:23:00,500
And you too!

1479
01:23:06,200 --> 01:23:09,400
It's OK, Interior Minister.

1480
01:23:10,000 --> 01:23:12,100
Even if they kill us,

1481
01:23:12,200 --> 01:23:14,800
we won't die!

1482
01:23:14,900 --> 01:23:17,500
Actually, it's for you
young people...

1483
01:23:19,600 --> 01:23:21,500
let's forget it. I'm too pushy.

1484
01:23:23,600 --> 01:23:25,500
By the way, radio gymnastics...

1485
01:23:25,700 --> 01:23:27,700
didn't come for a couple of days.

1486
01:23:28,800 --> 01:23:30,200
Instead,

1487
01:23:30,500 --> 01:23:32,600
let's dance the Charleston!

1488
01:23:33,200 --> 01:23:36,600
We'll teach you how,
Labour and Interior Ministers.

1489
01:23:36,800 --> 01:23:39,400
<i>Announcement for
the neighbourhood.</i>

1490
01:23:40,800 --> 01:23:43,900
<i>Air raid alarm that
you used to know,</i>

1491
01:23:44,500 --> 01:23:47,600
<i>an air raid alarm was just issued.</i>

1492
01:23:48,900 --> 01:23:51,600
<i>Several enemy targets...</i>

1493
01:23:51,800 --> 01:23:56,000
<i>have turned around the corner
and invading our skies.</i>

1494
01:23:56,500 --> 01:23:59,100
<i>Keep the highest alert.</i>

1495
01:23:59,500 --> 01:24:01,100
It's here!

1496
01:24:01,300 --> 01:24:04,000
The old newspaper collector
is helping us!

1497
01:24:04,100 --> 01:24:06,500
Dad! It's Dad's voice!

1498
01:24:06,700 --> 01:24:09,200
Why haven't I noticed?

1499
01:24:20,300 --> 01:24:21,600
They're here!

1500
01:24:22,100 --> 01:24:23,400
Bastards!

1501
01:24:34,000 --> 01:24:35,500
An old man's advice.

1502
01:24:36,000 --> 01:24:38,200
Here's my last words.

1503
01:24:40,500 --> 01:24:41,800
Our country...

1504
01:24:41,900 --> 01:24:44,800
wants to remain the
eastern Switzerland.

1505
01:24:46,000 --> 01:24:47,500
Foreign Minister,

1506
01:24:48,800 --> 01:24:50,600
you'll settle this...

1507
01:24:50,800 --> 01:24:53,600
diplomatically and peacefully.

1508
01:24:57,900 --> 01:24:59,700
If that fails,

1509
01:25:00,200 --> 01:25:02,900
and we must go into war,

1510
01:25:03,600 --> 01:25:05,000
Labour Minister,

1511
01:25:05,100 --> 01:25:07,300
you'll call the police.

1512
01:25:07,900 --> 01:25:10,500
We're asking the Japanese
police to help us?

1513
01:25:10,800 --> 01:25:13,600
I've paid the first half
of my citizen tax.

1514
01:25:14,900 --> 01:25:16,200
Excuse me,

1515
01:25:16,300 --> 01:25:18,900
I have some little things to do.

1516
01:25:20,500 --> 01:25:22,000
Me too!

1517
01:25:22,100 --> 01:25:23,800
Us too!

1518
01:25:24,300 --> 01:25:26,400
Finance Minister, you first.

1519
01:25:27,000 --> 01:25:28,400
The others,

1520
01:25:28,500 --> 01:25:30,900
line up according to age.

1521
01:25:43,900 --> 01:25:45,300
Open up!

1522
01:25:45,600 --> 01:25:47,300
It's open.

1523
01:25:47,600 --> 01:25:51,300
But don't touch the door knob.

1524
01:25:52,000 --> 01:25:54,900
If you do,
you're invading our territory.

1525
01:25:55,200 --> 01:25:58,600
Electric chair is your punishment.

1526
01:25:59,300 --> 01:26:00,900
Shut up, old hat!

1527
01:26:14,900 --> 01:26:16,300
Are they dead?

1528
01:26:16,500 --> 01:26:18,500
They asked for it.

1529
01:26:18,700 --> 01:26:20,400
But you just said...

1530
01:26:20,500 --> 01:26:22,300
The enemy said "old hat".

1531
01:26:22,400 --> 01:26:26,000
This is a taboo term.
So it's a different story.

1532
01:26:26,100 --> 01:26:27,300
This?

1533
01:26:28,200 --> 01:26:29,900
I was once...

1534
01:26:30,300 --> 01:26:33,200
an anti-aircraft artillery captain.

1535
01:26:35,900 --> 01:26:39,000
I'll shoot down a plane!

1536
01:28:34,000 --> 01:28:35,400
Idiot, reach!

1537
01:28:35,500 --> 01:28:37,000
OK! Reach!

1538
01:28:37,700 --> 01:28:40,500
- Reach!  - Come on!
- Who's he?

1539
01:28:40,600 --> 01:28:42,700
Iimuro the hitman. Chase him!

1540
01:28:52,900 --> 01:28:54,300
When did you come?

1541
01:28:54,400 --> 01:28:57,000
They don't understand what I said.

1542
01:28:58,100 --> 01:28:59,400
Never mind.

1543
01:28:59,900 --> 01:29:02,300
How's your countrymen?
Are they OK?

1544
01:29:07,200 --> 01:29:10,500
<i>A lot of them got hurt.</i>

1545
01:29:10,600 --> 01:29:12,100
<i>But not serious.</i>

1546
01:29:13,200 --> 01:29:15,000
<i>Because of the activity,</i>

1547
01:29:15,500 --> 01:29:17,200
<i>they're in high spirits.</i>

1548
01:29:19,200 --> 01:29:20,400
<i>But...</i>

1549
01:29:20,600 --> 01:29:22,500
<i>the primal scream of Tamiko...</i>

1550
01:29:22,800 --> 01:29:25,300
<i>revealed that
Education Minister was down.</i>

1551
01:29:26,100 --> 01:29:28,000
<i>The wounds weren't serious,</i>

1552
01:29:28,700 --> 01:29:30,500
<i>maybe his heart has gone out...</i>

1553
01:29:30,600 --> 01:29:32,900
<i>because of the vigorous activity?</i>

1554
01:29:34,800 --> 01:29:36,900
<i>We all agreed that he's dying.</i>

1555
01:29:37,600 --> 01:29:38,900
Hey.

1556
01:29:40,000 --> 01:29:41,300
Hey?

1557
01:29:42,500 --> 01:29:44,600
What's wrong with you all?

1558
01:29:46,300 --> 01:29:48,000
I'm...

1559
01:29:48,400 --> 01:29:50,000
OK.

1560
01:29:51,000 --> 01:29:52,400
Yes!

1561
01:29:52,600 --> 01:29:54,600
Your life line is long!

1562
01:29:55,200 --> 01:29:56,600
But...

1563
01:29:57,600 --> 01:29:59,100
I'm...

1564
01:29:59,900 --> 01:30:02,400
so sleepy.

1565
01:30:03,000 --> 01:30:04,900
No! Don't sleep!

1566
01:30:05,100 --> 01:30:07,600
Don't sleep! Education Minister.

1567
01:30:07,700 --> 01:30:11,200
We're all going to the
hot spring tomorrow!

1568
01:30:11,300 --> 01:30:13,000
No!

1569
01:30:13,100 --> 01:30:15,000
Don't sleep!

1570
01:30:15,200 --> 01:30:17,600
Do something, Labour Minister!

1571
01:30:17,800 --> 01:30:19,500
Put on some music!

1572
01:30:19,600 --> 01:30:21,200
Don't let him sleep!

1573
01:31:10,000 --> 01:31:11,900
Damn you!

1574
01:31:46,500 --> 01:31:47,800
Prime Minister.

1575
01:31:50,400 --> 01:31:52,900
Is there anything I can do?

1576
01:31:53,500 --> 01:31:55,200
I hate the establishment,

1577
01:31:55,400 --> 01:31:56,900
but I like you.

1578
01:31:57,100 --> 01:32:00,200
I have only one favour to ask.

1579
01:32:00,300 --> 01:32:01,500
OK.

1580
01:32:02,500 --> 01:32:05,400
If his death is unnatural,

1581
01:32:06,400 --> 01:32:09,900
there will be a
compulsory autopsy?

1582
01:32:11,400 --> 01:32:12,600
Yes.

1583
01:32:12,900 --> 01:32:16,500
Please give us one night.

1584
01:32:16,700 --> 01:32:18,000
That's all.

1585
01:32:18,800 --> 01:32:20,400
For him, we want...

1586
01:32:21,300 --> 01:32:24,300
a wake at a proper place.

1587
01:32:26,700 --> 01:32:28,000
OK.

1588
01:32:29,600 --> 01:32:31,300
But just one night.

1589
01:32:54,900 --> 01:32:56,200
Oh my!

1590
01:32:58,800 --> 01:33:01,100
The quake disturbed me,

1591
01:33:02,200 --> 01:33:04,300
I'll start counting again.

1592
01:33:05,900 --> 01:33:08,700
1... 2... 3...

1593
01:33:09,200 --> 01:33:11,500
- I was scared!
- It's OK now.

1594
01:33:13,000 --> 01:33:16,500
The cop called you and
said he's coming here.

1595
01:33:16,900 --> 01:33:18,200
What for?

1596
01:33:18,300 --> 01:33:20,200
He found Dad's body?

1597
01:33:20,500 --> 01:33:21,700
And?

1598
01:33:22,100 --> 01:33:24,900
He and the pickup were
thrown into Tokyo Bay.

1599
01:33:31,200 --> 01:33:33,900
The earthquake just then
was in Tokyo and Kanagawa.

1600
01:33:34,000 --> 01:33:35,700
5 on the seismic scale.

1601
01:33:35,900 --> 01:33:37,600
At the same time,

1602
01:33:37,700 --> 01:33:40,000
in the residential area
of Higashi-Tama,

1603
01:33:40,100 --> 01:33:43,600
a big explosion occurred
in Yamatai House.

1604
01:33:43,700 --> 01:33:47,300
No information on casualties
or any other things.

1605
01:33:47,500 --> 01:33:49,200
Jiro too?

1606
01:33:50,700 --> 01:33:52,700
It's like I played a trick,

1607
01:33:53,600 --> 01:33:56,100
or cutting corners. Sorry.

1608
01:34:04,000 --> 01:34:05,300
The cop?

1609
01:34:09,300 --> 01:34:11,000
Good evening.

1610
01:34:13,200 --> 01:34:15,200
Good evening.

1611
01:34:15,800 --> 01:34:17,200
Hey you!

1612
01:34:17,700 --> 01:34:19,700
Because of the thugs you hired,

1613
01:34:19,800 --> 01:34:21,500
Education Minister is dead.

1614
01:34:21,900 --> 01:34:23,600
We're having a wake here.

1615
01:34:24,800 --> 01:34:26,000
What?

1616
01:34:33,000 --> 01:34:34,500
- Labour Minister.
- Yes?

1617
01:34:34,700 --> 01:34:37,100
Let him lie on a bed.

1618
01:34:37,300 --> 01:34:39,400
Go upstairs.

1619
01:34:39,500 --> 01:34:41,200
- Jiro!  - What?
- Not upstairs.

1620
01:34:41,300 --> 01:34:43,100
It's not ready upstairs?

1621
01:34:43,200 --> 01:34:45,200
It's OK with me.

1622
01:35:26,100 --> 01:35:27,300
Now,

1623
01:35:27,500 --> 01:35:30,000
to prevent the ashes
from dropping,

1624
01:35:30,100 --> 01:35:34,000
please offer your incense
one by one.

1625
01:35:35,600 --> 01:35:37,000
A wake...

1626
01:35:37,100 --> 01:35:40,100
is to drink, eat, make merry...

1627
01:35:40,200 --> 01:35:42,600
as a tribute to the deceased.

1628
01:35:43,500 --> 01:35:45,800
In such a nice house,

1629
01:35:46,800 --> 01:35:49,000
there must be something...

1630
01:35:49,100 --> 01:35:51,900
to eat and drink.

1631
01:35:54,000 --> 01:35:55,800
Yes, madam?

1632
01:35:58,800 --> 01:36:00,700
Thank you very much.

1633
01:36:02,800 --> 01:36:05,200
And this gentleman,

1634
01:36:05,300 --> 01:36:07,600
have I seen you before?

1635
01:36:07,700 --> 01:36:09,100
His poster!

1636
01:36:09,700 --> 01:36:11,200
City Councillor...

1637
01:36:11,400 --> 01:36:13,000
Terao something.

1638
01:36:13,600 --> 01:36:15,100
Why are you here?

1639
01:36:15,200 --> 01:36:17,300
No, Labour Minister.

1640
01:36:18,000 --> 01:36:20,400
He must have a reason
to be here.

1641
01:36:20,600 --> 01:36:23,900
To have the City Councillor
at this wake,

1642
01:36:24,400 --> 01:36:25,800
it must be...

1643
01:36:26,200 --> 01:36:28,000
fate?

1644
01:36:30,500 --> 01:36:31,700
Now,

1645
01:36:31,800 --> 01:36:34,900
let us offer incense
to the deceased.

1646
01:36:35,700 --> 01:36:37,600
Please line up by age.

1647
01:36:38,200 --> 01:36:41,000
The youngest first.

1648
01:36:56,200 --> 01:36:59,700
<i>About the explosion just then,</i>

1649
01:36:59,900 --> 01:37:02,400
<i>luckily, there's no casualties.</i>

1650
01:37:02,500 --> 01:37:04,400
<i>End of bulletin.</i>

1651
01:37:14,600 --> 01:37:16,600
